        <div class="faq-right">
            <div class="faq-accordion">
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">Should I roll over my TSP when I retire?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">It depends on your situation. TSP has very low fees and solid fund options (especially the G Fund). However, an IRA rollover gives you more investment flexibility, Roth conversion opportunities, and simplified beneficiary planning. We analyze both options and recommend what's best for your specific situation.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">Is FEGLI worth keeping into retirement?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">Rarely. FEGLI costs increase dramatically after retirement, and most federal retirees can get better coverage at lower cost through private insurance. We analyze your coverage needs and compare FEGLI's post-retirement costs against private alternatives — many clients save thousands per year.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">How do I coordinate FEHB with Medicare?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">If you keep FEHB into retirement (which you should), it coordinates with Medicare as your primary coverage. Medicare becomes your primary insurance, and FEHB acts as secondary, often covering your Medicare out-of-pocket costs. This combination provides excellent coverage at a reasonable cost.</div>
                </button>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>
